  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verses 15, 16.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Targets...  shields",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The Authorized Version \"target\" is unfortunate, though it may with somewhat grim truth represent fact. It was a very large solid shield, originally made of some common material, as basketwork or wood, and covered with leather; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "these",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " with a plate of gold. The absence of the word \"shekel\" in each clause, both here and in Kings, leaves it open to us to suppose that the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "beka",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "half-",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "shekel, may be the right word. Now, the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "maneh",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 10:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), or pound, meant 100 bekas, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " 50 shekels. Thus the targets, or shields, had six manehs of gold to their plating each, and the lesser ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "bucklers",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (as we may perhaps call them) three manehs each. On the estimate that the shekel weighed 9 dwt. 3 gr., since the maneh weighed fifty shekels (100 ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "bekas",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", or half-shekels), the gold to a shield (target) may be put at something over 11 lbs. troy. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "The house of the forest of Lebanon",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " an armoury (see ",
        "children": []
